    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "> Let's say the user find a category that has a count under all those already displayed, the selected category will not appear if the sort is only on count:desc because the limit will be applied.\r\n\r\nGood point. I did not consider that case.\r\n\r\n> What would be the behaviour you would have expect on that case? Having an extra category displayed?\r\n\r\nI think you've handled it well considering your point above. But perhaps a selected item should only bubble to the top if it was not initially visible?\r\n\r\nLets say on load the visible category list is A, B, C and X, Y, Z are hidden.\r\n\r\nThe current behaviour completely makes sense if a user searches for Z and selects Z. \r\n\r\nHowever, its *mildly* disorientating for a user who has not *yet* searched inside a category who selects C and has the C and A swap positions on selection. \r\n\r\nIts a very minor issue but the difference in ordering is slightly noticeable when you have two menus (one with internal search and one without) on one page.\r\n\r\nThat might introduce complexities that are not worth it though, so happy to close this if it doesn't make sense to you.\r\n\r\n",
